					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm sorry, No Carrier, I didn't mean to like, offend you. And I didn't post two paragraphs of useless information. That's actually what you <strong>should</strong> do. I didn't mean to be like "I'm not going to help you, so fuck off." I tried to point you in the right direction, so you could truly <strong> understand</strong> what you are doing. And what are you trying to say when linking me to that forum? That has nothing to do with anything. I used to be like "Hey, I don't know how to do this. Show me a routine." But then I stopped doing that. I didn't understand the 6502, and that was a big mistake. So I was trying to prevent you from making that mistake. Not trying to say "Fuck off, I won't help."
<br />
<br />And thank you for digging up old post that was like 100 years old, and for trying to make me feel dumb in every way possible. It didn't work. Go here: <!-- w --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.freewebs.com/the_bott/gbaguy.zip">www.freewebs.com/the_bott/gbaguy.zip</a><!-- w --> . This guys site is dead, and I seem to be the only one that downloaded his tutorials, a long time ago. I admit, I should've linked you hear instead of saying "Go learn 6502 somewhere else, then you'll truly understand." He'll say in the beggining of these tutorials, "You must know the 6502 by now!" But as you read, you'll realize, he's teaching you 6502 as you go along. He uses NESASM, so you'll need that. Once these tutorials are read, you want to leave them behind in the dust. They are fairly inaccurate in many aspects, but they really boosted me into the world of NESdev.
<br />
<br />EDIT: Oh, these tutorials are on my site, but the guy that made these tutorials, his site is dead.
<br />
<br />Celius wrote:
<br />This isn't an emulation question, but I ask it here, because people only seem to be active here. But, I'm not sure about how to do sound stuff. I can make a note, but I can't make it change or anything. I know you have to do something in 4017, but what? can someone give me an example of a sound code that has changing notes and rythyms? thank you...
<br />
<br />I see I was like that like my first week on NESdev. But I learned that you shouldn't be like that, you won't really learn. I didn't learn from whatever they posted below that. I don't remember what they posted about! But the tutorials I linked you to teach you as you read. And I apollogize for coming off rude, I didn't mean to sound like I was telling you to fuck off. I suppose you should be shown some sample routines, and pick them apart as you learn about the 6502.</div>

					
